y a subtle confidence, creating a mood of casual composure. However, additional emphasis on the facial expression could enhance the emotional depth of the character.","improvement_tips":["Experiment with facial features to express a stronger mood or character emotion.","Consider body language clues or props that might contribute to the overall atmosphere.","Use reference models to study expressions and stances that express intended emotions."]}}	\N	10	The basic gesture of a relaxed, cocky stance reads clearly and the major landmarks (shoulders, hips, knees) line up in a believable contrapposto. However, the head is undersized, the forearms appear elongated, and the legs do not convincingly carry the figure’s weight, which flattens the pose.	{"Begin with a light stick-figure or mannequin to lock in head-to-body ratios (7–7½ heads tall) before refining details","Check limb lengths by measuring one part against another with your pencil—elbow should roughly line up with waist, wrists with crotch","Place a quick value mass under the grounded foot to clarify where the weight sits and adjust the tilt of the hips accordingly"}	8	Lines are exploratory and capture some energy, but many contours are repeatedly restated, giving the drawing a scratchy, hesitant feel and obscuring clean structure.	{"Commit to a single, confident sweep once the placement feels right—practice drawing each contour in one or two strokes","Use line weight variation: darker, thicker lines for foreground or weight-bearing edges","lighter lines for softer or receding areas","Try warm-up exercises (straight lines, ellipses, figure-eight loops) to build muscle memory before working on the figure"}	v1	0		{}	0		{}	0		{}	7	Facial features have a hint of modeling, yet most of the body relies on flat outline; folds on the jacket and pants are indicated but not tied to the underlying form, so the figure feels 2-D.	{"Block in simple 3-D primitives (cylinders for limbs, a box for the pelvis) and shade their light-