 umbrella and arms.	{"Choose a light source direction and deepen shadows on the underside of the umbrella, inner arms, and between the knees and coat.","Use graduated tone or cross-hatching to round the head and boots rather than outlining every fold.","Introduce cast shadows on the ground to anchor the figure more firmly in space."}	16	The tucked pose, down-turned gaze, and tiny umbrella convey a sweet, introspective moment of shelter, and the limited pink accent adds a gentle warmth. The surrounding environment, though faint, hints at a rainy day.	{"Reinforce atmosphere with a few lightly suggested raindrops or puddle ripples to heighten the story.","Emphasize facial expression by refining eye and brow shapes or adding a slight mouth curve.","Push contrast (darker shadows, brighter highlights) to make the cozy mood more palpable."}	0		{}	2025-05-31	quick sketch
eb0b17e0-7708-4b9c-9710-5ac2695b0126	Field Notes: Two Skittering Studies	o3 re-eval	https://res.cloudinary.com/djhpg0skf/image/upload/v1743290897/artwork/ze0gep6hegmlu3ueznq6.jpg	artwork/ze0gep6hegmlu3ueznq6	JoeK	2025-03-29 23:28:24.748497+00	Standard evaluation v0	{"generated_title":"Insect Interlude","proportion_and_structure":{"score":12,"rationale":"The proportions of the insects are somewhat exaggerated but maintain a recognizable form. While the general structure of the bodies is clear, certain elements sacrifice accuracy for stylistic choice.","improvement_tips":["Study the anatomy of insects for better proportion.","Use reference images to understand size relationships better.","Experiment with different perspectives to enhance structural accuracy."]},"line_quality":{"score":14,"rationale":"The lines demonstrate a dynamic and energetic quality, though they lack some consistency and control. There is good variation, but some lines appear shaky or overly loose.","improvement_tips":["Practice drawing with more deliberate strokes to enhance control.","Experiment with different pen pressure for varied line thickness.","Consider using a smoother paper for cleaner line work."]},"form_and_volume":{"score":10,"rationale":"There is a suggestion of volume in the bodies of the insects, but the lack of effective shading or dimensional modeling leaves them feeling flat. The outlines dominate the drawing without significant depth.","improvement_tips":["Incorporate shading techniques to create depth and volume.","Study light sources and how they affect the form of subjects.","Experiment with cross-hatching or stippling to enhance dimensionality."]},"mood_and_expression":{"score":11,"rationale":"The sketched insects convey a playful, whimsical feeling, but there is limited emotional depth. The clarity of their expressions could be enhanced to evoke a stronger mood.","improvement_tips":["Consider infusing personality traits into the insects to evoke more emotion.","Experiment with different poses or facial expressions to enhance character.","Use background elements or colors to further convey mood."]}}	\N	10	Basic body plans for both insects are recognisable, with heads, thoraxes, abdomens, wings and legs placed in the correct order. However, limb lengths vary from joint to joint and the wing bases sit higher than they would on an actual grasshopper or cockroach-type insect, so the overall anatomy feels tentative.	{"Lightly block in each major mass (head, thorax, abdomen) with simple shapes before adding detail","use reference photos to check relative sizes","Run a centre-line through the body and add hinge dots where each leg segment meets","this keeps joints aligned","Study a real insect side-on and measure proportions (e.g., abdomen ≈ 1.5× thorax length) to build a mental ‘ratio library’"}	7	There’s an energetic search-line approach that shows you were feeling out the form, but most strokes are equally thin and scribbly, creating visual noise and making it hard to know which lines are final decisions.	{"Use two stages: first very light, loose exploratory lines","then go back with slower, darker, single strokes to commit to the final contour","Vary pressure—thicker or darker where the form turns toward shadow, lighter where it faces light—to add hierarchy","Practise straight-line and curved-line drills (ghosting, ellipses) for steadier, more confident marks"}	v1	0		{}	0		{}	0		{}	5	Because all lines sit on the contour and there is almost no indication of overlapping planes or subtle shading, the insects read mostly as flat silhouettes with interior scribbles rather than solid volumes.	{"Add cross-contour lines around the abdomen and legs to show how each cylinder turns in space","Introduce a quick light-source—shade the underside of the body and the far legs slightly to push them back","When drawing wings, indicate the translucent overlap and foreshortened edges to reinforce depth"}	8	The loose, exploratory strokes give the sketches a spontaneous ‘field-journal’ charm, and the tilted heads with visible eyes lend a spark of character, but the lack of tonal variation limits the emotional punch.	{"Play with pose: angle one insect as if about to leap or extend antennae further forward to create tension","Use selective darks (e.g., the eye spot or deep shadow under the thorax) to create focal points and atmosphere","Experiment with a light wash or hatching background halo to separate the insects from the page and suggest environment"}	0		{}	2025-02-23	quick sketch
9927da66-2abb-4fa2-a8ee-a1612a90a621	“Entomological Field Notes”	o3 re-eval	https://res.cloudinary.com/djhpg0skf/image/upload/v1743290814/artwork/whaz1aj4fo20pbxbb7b7.jpg	artwork/whaz1aj4fo20pbxbb7b7	JoeK	2025-03-29 23:27:03.307507+00	Standard evaluation v0	{"generated_title":"Insect Anatomy Exploration","proportion_and_structure":{"score":14,"rationale":"The proportions of the insects are generally good, but some elements, particularly the legs and wings, appear a bit inconsistent in their scale and position. The overall structure is recognizable but could benefit from more attention to anatomical accuracy.","improvement_tips":["Study insect anatomy more closely to improve accuracy in proportions and details.","Consider using a reference image to ensure the various components are aligned properly.","Sketch lightly first to place major forms before refining details."]},"line_quality":{"score":16,"rationale":"The lines are mostly confident and controlled, creating a clear representation of the forms. However, there are areas where the quality could be improved by varying line weight to give depth and interest to the forms.","improvement_tips":["Experiment with varying line thickness to differentiate between foreground and background elements.","Incorporate additional hatching or cross-hatching to enhance texture and shadow.","Practice creating smoother, more deliberate strokes for clarity."]},"form_and_volume":{"score":13,"rationale":"The drawing suggests some three-dimensionality, especially in the larger insect, but overall, the forms could be improved for a more realistic volume. The shading is minimal, making it harder to perceive depth.","improvement_tips":["Add shading to define light sources and create a sense of volume.","Use contour lines to suggest roundness in the forms and improve their three-dimensionality.","Experiment with light and shadow to better depict the structure of the insects."]},"mood_and_expression":{"score":12,"rationale":"The mood is somewhat neutral, largely due to the scientific or observational nature of the sketches. To evoke more emotion or atmosphere, consider adding contextual elements or varying gestures.","improvement_tips":["Incorporate dynamic poses or interactions between insects to engage viewers' emotions.","Consider adding environmental elements to create context and enhance the narrative of the piece.","Experiment with different angles or perspectives to instill movement."]}}	\N	13	All three insects are built from clear cylinders, boxes and ellipses, so the basic anatomy reads correctly; however, a few legs float without joints and the bee’s head-thorax connection feels pinched, so the overall balance is slightly off.	{"Before committing to ink, ghost in all limb joints as dots to ensure every segment has a clear attachment point","Use a light center-line down each body segment to keep bilateral symmetry consistent","Compare negative spaces (e.g., gap between legs and body) against reference photos to spot proportion errors early"}	12	The artist explores both thick contour lines and thin construction marks, but many strokes are repeatedly restated, producing a fuzzy outline and occasional tangles where forms intersect.	{"Try a single, deliberate stroke for each contour","if it misses, redraw next to it rather than over it to keep edges crisp","Vary pressure: lighter for hidden or receding edges, heavier for foreground lines to add depth","Warm-up with straight-line and ellipse drills to build wrist confidence before starting the insect studies"}	v1	0		{}	0		{}	0		{}	14	Cross-contour wraps and segmented shells give a decent sense of three-dimensionality, especially in sketch #5 climbing the leaf, yet the absence of light/shadow and tonal hierarchy keeps the insects looking primarily like wireframes.	{"Introduce one consistent light source and add simple hatch shadows on the downward planes to lock volumes in space","Slightly overlap body segments and let nearer forms occlude farther ones to reinforce depth","Use thicker, darker lines on silhouettes that face the viewer and thinner ones on those turning away to imply curvature"}	6	As scientific studies, the drawings are functional rather than emotive; only the pose of #5, clinging to a leaf, hints at behavior, while the others feel static.	{"Experiment with dynamic poses—e.g., wings mid-beat, mandibles open—to inject life into the sketches","Add contextual cues like foliage silhouettes or cast shadows to place the insects in an environment","Play with line rhythm","a few sweeping gesture lines can convey motion or tension even in small studies"}	0		{}	2025-02-22	quick sketch
1690df61-3a25-46b6-b19e-4c4a5e49d9c8	“Whirlwind of Blades – Jett in Motion”	Standard evaluation v0	https://res.cloudinary.com/djhpg0skf/image/upload/v1745755224/artwork/nxonksstbwcl2vh3geei.png	artwork/nxonksstbwcl2vh3geei	Riot	2025-04-27 12:00:51.910731+00	Standard evaluation v0	{"generated_title":"“Whirlwind of Blades – Jett in Motion”","proportion_and_structure":{"score":17,"rationale":"The figure’s anatomy, gesture, and weapon placement are well-planned and feel natural, conveying a believable athletic stance. Minor elongation in the forearm and slightly narrow hips are the only subtle proportional slips.","improvement_tips":["Double-check limb lengths with simple mannequin under-drawings before inking.","Widen the pelvic block 3–5 % to better echo realistic hip width.","Mirror-flip the drawing while sketching to catch small proportional asymmetries."]},"line_quality":{"score":18,"rationale":"Clean, confident contours vary from bold outer silhouettes to lighter interior accents, effectively guiding focus and describing form and material differences.","improvement_tips":["Introduce a few more tapering strokes on soft fabric folds for added subtlety.","Use broken or textured lines on metallic edges to suggest wear.","Experiment with lost-and-found edges in areas where light overpowers line (e.g., lit forearm)."]},"form_and_volume":{"score":17,"rationale":"Solid cross-contour indications in the arms, torso, and swirling energy give the character convincing mass and depth.","improvement_tips":["Deepen core shadows beneath overlapping elements (belt to pants, forearm over torso) to push layers apart.","Add slight reflected light on the shadow side of limbs to round them further.","Use elliptical guide lines on throwing knives to reinforce their cylindrical volumes."]},"mood_and_expression":{"score":16,"rationale":"The confident stance, dynamic swirl, and determined facial expression create a clear sense of motion and resolve befitting the character.","improvement_tips":["Tilt the head or narrow the eyes a touch more to heighten intensity.","Accentuate motion blur on a few airborne knives for extra dynamism.","Consider a darker background wash to amplify drama around the illuminated hand."]},"value_and_light":{"score":15,"rationale":"The piece relies mainly on line with selective tonal washes; light source is readable but contrast could be pushed to separate planes more strongly.","improvement_tips":["Increase the darkest darks in glove interiors and under the belt to extend the value range.","Introduce mid-tone washes on the lower legs to gradate away from the focal upper body.","Highlight the energy swirl with a subtle rim light to clarify its glow."]},"detail_and_texture":{"score":16,"rationale":"Material cues—sleek metal blades, loose fabric, and glowing energy—are distinct and applied without clutter.","improvement_tips":["Add micro-scratches or specular flecks on metal edges for heightened realism.","Suggest fabric weave or subtle seams on the pants in the mid-tones.","Vary line weight on hair strands to enhance texture without over-rendering."]},"composition_and_perspective":{"score":17,"rationale":"The spiral energy and flying daggers frame the figure nicely, guiding the eye in a circular motion while maintaining a solid three-quarter perspective.","improvement_tips":["Shift one knife slightly forward in perspective to create a stronger foreground element.","Fade the bottom swirl’s line weight to create atmospheric depth.","Consider a slight tilt to the canvas (Dutch angle) for an even more dramatic composition."]},"overall_realism":{"score":16,"rationale":"While stylized, the anatomy, perspective, and material indications produce a believable, cohesive scene. Enhanced lighting and textural nuance would push it closer to full realism.","improvement_tips":["Broaden the value spectrum for more tangible lighting.","Refine small proportional tweaks (forearm, hips) for anatomical polish.","Integrate soft cast shadows on the ground plane to anchor the character firmly."]} }	\N	17	The figure’s anatomy, gesture, and weapon placement are well-planned and feel natural, conveying a believable athletic stance. Minor elongation in the forearm and slightly narrow hips are the only subtle proportional slips.	{"Double-check limb lengths with simple mannequin under-drawings before inking.","Widen the pelvic block 3–5 % to better echo realistic hip width.","Mirror-flip the drawing while sketching to catch small proportional asymmetries."}	18	Clean, confident contours vary from bold outer silhouettes to lighter interior accents, effectively guiding focus and describing form and material differences.	{"Introduce a few more tapering strokes on soft fabric folds for added subtlety.","Use broken or textured lines on metallic edges to suggest wear.","Experiment with lost-and-found edges in areas where light overpowers line (e.g., lit forearm)."}	v1	15	The piece relies mainly on line with selective tonal washes; light source is readable but contrast could be pushed to separate planes more strongly.	{"Increase the darkest darks in glove interiors and under the belt to extend the value range.","Introduce mid-tone washes on the lower legs to gradate away from the focal upper body.","Highlight the energy swirl with a subtle rim light to clarify its glow."}	16	Material cues—sleek metal blades, loose fabric, and glowing energy—are distinct and applied without clutter.	{"Add micro-scratches or specular flecks on metal edges for heightened realism.","Suggest fabric weave or subtle seams on the pants in the mid-tones.","Vary line weight on hair strands to enhance texture without over-rendering."}	17	The spiral energy and flying daggers frame the figure nicely, guiding the eye in a circular motion while maintaining a solid three-quarter perspective.	{"Shift one knife slightly forward in perspective to create a stronger foreground element.","Fade the bottom swirl’s line weight to create atmospheric depth.","Consider 