ue steps (light, mid-tone, shadow, accent) instead of single flat colors to turn forms.","Shade along the contour of each form (curved strokes around the cheek, cylindrical strokes on the neck) to enhance volume."]},"mood_and_expression":{"score":14,"rationale":"The Sultan’s wide-open mouth and bulging eyes contrast nicely with Prince Ali’s proud upward gaze, giving the scene narrative tension despite the bare background.","improvement_tips":["Push facial exaggeration further—stretch the Sultan’s eyebrows or compress his chin to heighten emotion.","Add minimal background cues (drapery, palace columns) or cast shadows between the two figures to reinforce atmosphere.","Experiment with warmer or cooler colored pencils behind each character to amplify their emotional temperature."]}}	\N	12	The stylized heads are recognizable and the key landmarks (eyes, nose, mouth, turban brim) sit roughly where they belong, but the Sultan’s facial width, the placement of Aladdin’s ear, and some neck-to-shoulder connections feel mis-aligned or uneven.	{"Lightly block in simple 3-D shapes (spheres for skulls, wedges for jaws, cylinders for necks) before committing to final lines.","Check angles by turning the page upside-down or using a mirror—misalignments jump out instantly.","Use a center-line down each face to keep features symmetrical and correctly wrapped around the head."}	11	There is a lively mix of thin and heavy strokes, but many contours look hesitant or over-traced, and some outlines fight with interior hatching, muddying the read.	{"Practice drawing each contour with one decisive stroke rather than many short ones—warm-up with 30-second gesture lines.","Reserve thicker, darker lines for foreground silhouettes and areas of shadow; keep inner details lighter to create hierarchy.","Clean up or erase construction lines once the main line is chosen to give the drawing a confident finish."}	v1	0		{}	0		{}	0		{}	10	Basic shading under the turbans and along cheeks hints at three-di