fb82b2da-2dcb-4f95-aa1d-9cfa10df36f7	The Curious Side-Glance	Standard evaluation v0	https://res.cloudinary.com/djhpg0skf/image/upload/v1747184849/artwork/qvwih6xpd6wpdyceuckn.jpg	artwork/qvwih6xpd6wpdyceuckn	JoeK	2025-05-14 01:08:04.541292+00	Standard evaluation v0	{"generated_title":"The Curious Side-Glance","proportion_and_structure":{"score":11,"rationale":"The overall head tilt and shoulder angle are readable, but the eyes sit on slightly different axes, the far shoulder is narrow for the torso, and the cranium is a bit shallow at the crown.","improvement_tips":["Lightly map the eye-line, brow-line, and center-line of the head before committing to features.","Block in the basic mass of the ribcage and shoulder girdle with simple boxes or ovals to check width before detailing.","Flip the drawing (or view it in a mirror) during the sketch stage to catch asymmetries quickly."]},"line_quality":{"score":12,"rationale":"There’s a nice contrast between soft shading and darker contour lines, yet many strokes feel sketchy or hesitant and lack consistent taper or weight.","improvement_tips":["Use a single confident stroke for major contours, lifting the pencil at the end to create a natural taper.","Vary pressure deliberately: lighter lines for interior construction, heavier for foreground edges or cast shadows.","Practice warm-up line exercises (straight lines, ellipses) to build muscle memory and steadiness."]},"form_and_volume":{"score":10,"rationale":"Shading around the nose, lips, and jaw suggests some 3-D form, but inconsistent light logic flattens the hair mass and shoulder.","improvement_tips":["Choose a clear light direction and keep all planes consistent—shadow under the bangs should match that on the neck.","Simplify the head into basic planes (Loomis or Asaro head) and shade each plane distinctly before softening transitions.","Introduce reflected light on shadowed areas to round the volumes further without losing contrast."]},"mood_and_expression":{"score":14,"rationale":"The off-center gaze, parted lips, and slight head tilt communicate a subtle, inquisitive mood that engages the viewer.","improvement_tips":["Accent the eye focus by tightening the iris/eyelid alignment and adding a crisp highlight.","Slightly lift one eyebrow or soften the mouth corner to push the chosen emotion further.","Surround the face with value contrast (darker background on the eye-side) to direct attention to the expression."]},"value_and_light":{"score":9,"rationale":"There’s an attempt at shadow under the chin and within the hair, but the value range is narrow and mid-tones dominate, reducing depth.","improvement_tips":["Establish a five-step value scale on a scrap sheet, then ensure each one appears somewhere in the portrait.","Deepen core shadows (eye sockets, under the jaw, inner hair masses) while preserving small areas of clean paper for highlights.","Blend with a tissue or stump in large shadow areas, then re-define dark accents with a sharp pencil for crispness."]},"detail_and_texture":{"score":8,"rationale":"Individual hair strands are hinted, and lip texture is touched in, yet the hair mass feels fuzzy and skin reads as a single grainy tone.","improvement_tips":["Think of hair in big clumps first; indicate just a few well-placed strand lines to convey direction and sheen.","Introduce subtle pores or temperature shifts (cool shadows, warm lights) with light cross-hatching rather than uniform smudge.","Reserve tiny, sharp highlights on lips and eyes to differentiate slick surfaces from matte skin."]},"composition_and_perspective":{"score":12,"rationale":"The three-quarter pose creates visual interest and negative space, but the figure is low on the page and near-tangent to the right edge, and the shoulder perspective is slightly off.","improvement_tips":["Lift the portrait slightly upward or crop tighter to avoid the empty top margin and strengthen focus.","Use a quick thumbnail grid to explore alternate placements before starting the final sheet.","Check shoulder and collarbone angles against a horizon line or reference photo to ensure they converge consistently."]},"overall_realism":{"score":11,"rationale":"The likeness is recognizable and features are generally correct, yet proportional slips, shallow value range, and tentative lines keep it from full believability.","improvement_tips":["Spend the first 10–15 minutes on accurate block-in before shading.","Push darkest darks and lightest lights to expand contrast.","Integrate edges—lose some lines into shadows and sharpen focal ones to mimic how the eye sees."]}}	\N	11	The overall head tilt and shoulder angle are readable, but the eyes sit on slightly different axes, the far shoulder is narrow for the torso, and the cranium is a bit shallow at the crown.	{"Lightly map the eye-line, brow-line, and center-line of the head before committing to features.","Block in the basic mass of the ribcage and shoulder girdle with simple boxes or ovals to check width before detailing.","Flip the drawing (or view it in a mirror) during the sketch stage to catch asymmetries quickly."}	12	There’s a nice contrast between soft shading and darker contour lines, yet many strokes feel sketchy or hesitant and lack consistent taper or weight.	{"Use a single confident stroke for major contours, lifting the pencil at the end to create a natural taper.","Vary pressure deliberately: lighter lines for interior construction, heavier for foreground edges or cast shadows.","Practice warm-up line exercises (straight lines, ellipses) to build muscle memory and steadiness."}	v1	9	There’s an attempt at shadow under the chin and within the hair, but the value range is narrow and mid-tones dominate, reducing depth.	{"Establish a five-step value scale on a scrap sheet, then ensure each one appears somewhere in the portrait.","Deepen core shadows (eye sockets, under the jaw, inner hair masses) while preserving small areas of clean paper for highlights.","Blend with a tissue or stump i