lear light source and shade every major volume (arm, torso, hair mass) with a three-value system: light, mid-tone, core shadow.","Use gradated strokes that follow the contour of each form (e.g., curved strokes around the arm) to reinforce roundness.","Add cast shadows—such as the arm onto the torso or glasses onto the cheeks—to anchor the figure in space."]},"mood_and_expression":{"score":15,"rationale":"The upturned sunglasses, cocked head and slight smirk convey a lively, confident mood that comes through immediately, and the colored lenses add personality. Because the background and hands are unfinished, the atmosphere could be pushed further.","improvement_tips":["Carry the playful attitude into the hands—finish the gesturing hand with expressive fingers to enhance character.","Suggest a minimal background prop (pool rail, summer sky wash) to place the child in a fun setting without overcrowding.","Consider heightening eye highlights or a splash of brighter color on the glasses to amplify focal energy."]}}	\N	14	The head, torso and sunglasses align believably, and the playful lean of the figure reads clearly. However, the forearms appear slightly thick and short, and the shoulder-to-elbow rhythm on the viewer’s left side feels stiff, hinting that the armature underneath wasn’t fully resolved.	{"Lightly block in the whole gesture with simple cylinders and boxes before committing to contour—this will keep arm lengths consistent.","Check negative shapes around the arms and waist in a mirror or by flipping the paper to spot proportion errors.","Use a quick measurement system (e.g., head-length units) to verify shoulder width and elbow placement."}	12	The drawing shows confident dark outlines in the face and glasses, but elsewhere the strokes vary between tentative and heavy, with some construction lines left visible. Cross-hatching on the shirt is playful yet uniform, lacking intentional variation.	{"Practice continuous, single-direction contour passes to build clea